Notes on Atrial Fibrillation dataset analysis

JoÃ£o Miguel Alves

2023-02-03



Introduction

The ATLAS score [1] provides a risk estimate to predict the rate of Atrial Fibrillation (AF) recurrence after pulmonary vein isolation (PVI) procedure. However, it suffers from the typical limitations of clinical scores, such as the use of a small number of independent variables for the prediction of a single dependent variable, which remains unchanged throughout the patientâs clinical course.

The ATLAS score is based on 5 independent variables, being: Age, Sex, Smoking habits, Left atrial volume (LAV), and occurrence of paroxysmal AF. It is strongly dependent on the measurement of the LAV as its main driver, which is not always possible to obtain. Similarly to other clinical scores, it is unfeasible to be calculated in the absence of any of its predicting variables.

An additional limitation is that it establishes an upfront risk profile, which cannot be revised or readjusted during the patientâs subsequent follow-up. Also, other potential risk factors (as eg. Epicardial fat or Obstructive Sleep Apnea) are not taken into consideration for the calculation of this score.

This analysis proposes the structuring and fitting of a Bayesian Network (BN) that can represent medical knowledge on this field. This model can then be used to predict the occurrence of Atrial Fibrillation in patients, as an enhanced alternative to the ATLAS score.



Dataset

# Read dataset, as data frame
ds <- read.csv(file.path("data", "FA_dataset_pretreated.csv"),
               stringsAsFactors = TRUE) |> as.data.frame()

# Convert all logical variables to factors
ds[sapply(ds, is.logical)] <- lapply(ds[sapply(ds, is.logical)], as.factor)

The data set for this analysis consists in clinical data from 495 patients being followed at the Cardiac Arrhythmia Service of a public hospital in Portugal. It includes 12 categorical variables, with 1 observation per patient.

All patients underwent an ablation procedure to minimize the occurrence of Atrial Fibrillation (AF). The target outcome variable is AF_relapse, indicating whether or not a patient experienced an AF relapse after the ablation procedure.

Network structure

The structure of the Bayesian network was built based on expert knowledge as well as inference from data.

White list

On the expert knowledge side, we opted to associate the diseases tracked on the dataset with their known risk factors. This knowledge is include as a whitelist, the list of relations to be present in the network structure. Risk factors were included for Diabetes, High Blood Pressure (HBP) and Obstructive Sleep Apnea (OSA).

Additionally,for this whitelist, we included all 5 predictive variables for AF relapse, previously identified for the ATLAS score. On top of these, 2 other variables were included as potential risk factors for the same outcome, as suggested by medical literature: Epicardial fat (EpiFat) [2] and Obstructive Sleep Apnea (OSA) [3, 4]

dag_white_list <- as.data.frame(tibble::tribble(
  #--------------- |-----------
  ~from,            ~to,
  #--- Diabetes risk-factors
  "Age",            "Diabetes",
  "Sex",            "Diabetes",
  "BMI",            "Diabetes",
  #--- High Blood Pressure risk-factors
  "Age",            "HBP",
  "Sex",            "HBP",
  "Alcohol",        "HBP",
  "Smoking_active", "HBP",
  "BMI",            "HBP",
  "Diabetes",       "HBP",
  #--- OSA risk-factors
  "Age",            "OSA",
  "BMI",            "OSA",
  "HBP",            "OSA",
  "Smoking_active", "OSA",
  "Sex",            "OSA",
  # "Diabetes",     "OSA", # There is a correlation, but the direction is not clear
  #--- ATLAS related
  "Age",            "AF_relapse",
  "Sex",            "AF_relapse",
  "LeftAtrium_Vol", "AF_relapse",
  "Smoking_active", "AF_relapse",
  "Persistent_AF",  "AF_relapse",
  #--- Other expert knowledge
  "EpiFat",         "AF_relapse",
  "OSA",            "AF_relapse",
))

Black list

As blacklist, we assumed any arcs directed to Age or Sex as to be avoided. These variables are independent of any other, and therefore should not receive any directed arc.

features_all <- names(ds)
bl_01 <- data.frame(from = features_all[features_all != "Age"], to = "Age")
bl_02 <- data.frame(from = features_all[features_all != "Sex"], to = "Sex")
dag_black_list <- rbind(bl_01, bl_02)

Additional arcs here left to be discovered by a âhillâclimbingâ algorithm.

dag <- bnlearn::hc(ds,
                   whitelist = dag_white_list,
                   blacklist = dag_black_list)

Plot structure

The network structure is presented in the figure below.

Colored nodes indicate:

  • [grey] : Whitelisted diseases with attributed risk factors (Diabetes, HBP, OSA)
  • [sand] : ATLASâ 5 predictive variables (Age, Sex, Smoking_active, LeftAtrium_Vol, Persistent_AF)
  • [blue] : Outcome variable (AF_Relapse)

Light grey arcs indicate whitelisted relations, ie. known risk factors. Orange colored arcs indicate relations discovered by the hillâclimbing algorithm, sugesting meaningful relations between variables.

Note than OSA, Persistent_AF and LeftAtrium_Vol were set to be directly linked to AF_relapse (whitelisted). Interestingly, the model also suggests other links not previously defined:

  • OSA â> Persistent_AF
  • Persistent_AF â> LeftAtrium_vol

Also, unsurprisingly, the model relates the body mass index BMI with the epicardial fat EpiFat.

Regarding the outcome variable AF_relapse, the model did not find any other relevant link apart from those previously whitelisted.

Model training

Split training and testing

Data set was split into train and test sets, with a partition ratio of 90:10.

In this data set, OSA and Age are the most imbalanced predicting features. In order to have a more balanced split for these classes, we created a dummy variable combining both variables, and used it as target for splitting the data partitions. This dummy variable was then deleted immediately after partitioning.

  ds$dummy <- as.factor(paste(ds$OSA, ds$Age))

  set.seed(811)
  train_index <- caret::createDataPartition(ds$dummy, p = 0.90, list = FALSE)
  ds$dummy <- NULL
  ds_train <- ds[train_index,]
  ds_test <- ds[-train_index,]

Learn model

The model was set to learn the conditional probabilities between features on the train set, based on the previously learnt network structure. Conditional probabilities were calculated by a classic Bayesian posterior estimator (method = bayes).

fit.bayes <- bn.fit(dag, data = ds_train, method = "bayes", iss = 10)



Testing all parent nodes

Calculate relapse probabilities

For this step, we calculated the conditional probability of AF relapse for each patient at the test set, considering their current clinical conditions. The calculation considered the clinical state for all AF_relapse parent nodes: Age, Sex, Smoking_active, Persistent_AF, LeftAtrium_Vol, EpiFat and OSA.

# Get parent nodes for "AF_relapse" from model
parent_nodes <-
  bnlearn::arcs(dag) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  dplyr::filter(to == "AF_relapse") %>%
  dplyr::select(from) %>%
  unlist() %>%
  unname()

# Create new column for computed relapse probabilities
ds_test[, "Relapse_prob_pred7"] <- NA

# Fill in probabilities variable 
n_tries <- 10
n_means <- 5

for (patient in rownames(ds_test)) {
  evidence_patient <- ds_test[patient, parent_nodes]
  
  # Calculate probability of relapse as average of N queries to model
  Relapse_prob_pred7 <- array(NA, n_means)
  for (n in 1:length(Relapse_prob_pred7)) {
    Relapse_prob_pred7[n] <-
      sapply(matrix(NA, n_tries), FUN = function(x) {
        bnlearn::cpquery(fitted = fit.bayes,
                         event = (AF_relapse == TRUE),
                         evidence = ((Sex == evidence_patient$Sex) &
                                       (Age == evidence_patient$Age) &
                                       (Smoking_active == evidence_patient$Smoking_active) &
                                       (Persistent_AF == evidence_patient$Persistent_AF) &
                                       (LeftAtrium_Vol == evidence_patient$LeftAtrium_Vol) &
                                       (EpiFat == evidence_patient$EpiFat) &
                                       (OSA == evidence_patient$OSA))
                         )
      }) |> mean(na.rm = TRUE)
  }
  
  Relapse_prob_pred7 <- Relapse_prob_pred7 |> mean(na.rm = TRUE) |> round(digits = 3)
  ds_test[patient, "Relapse_prob_pred7"] <- Relapse_prob_pred7
}

Evaluate performance

model_roc_pred7 <- pROC::roc(ds_test$AF_relapse, ds_test$Relapse_prob_pred7)
model_cutoff_pred7 <- coords(model_roc_pred7, x = "best", ret = "threshold") |> unlist() |> unname()

Modelâs performance for classifying AF relapse with all parent nodes (7 predictors) was evaluated through the Area Under the ROC curve, with a computed AUC value of 0.830. The best cutâoff value for this classification was calculated at 0.291.

ds_test$prediction_pred7 <- ifelse(ds_test$Relapse_prob_pred7 < model_cutoff_pred7,
                             levels(ds_test$AF_relapse)[1],
                             levels(ds_test$AF_relapse)[2]) |> factor()
cm_pred7 <- caret::confusionMatrix(data = ds_test$prediction_pred7,
                             reference = ds_test$AF_relapse,
                             positive = "TRUE")
print(cm_pred7)

The figure below presents a dotplot exhibiting the estimated probabilities of AF relapse for all patients in the test set. Dots are split according to reported occurrence of AF relapse for those patients. The dashed horizontal line shows the calculated cutâoff value.

model_metrics_pred7 <- paste0(
  "AUC: ",  sprintf("%.3f", model_roc_pred7$auc), "\n",
  "Accu: ", sprintf("%.3f", cm_pred7$overall["Accuracy"]), "\n",
  "Sens: ", sprintf("%.3f", cm_pred7$byClass["Sensitivity"]), "\n",
  "Spec: ", sprintf("%.3f", cm_pred7$byClass["Specificity"])
)

dotplot_pred7 <-
  ggplot(data = ds_test, aes(x = AF_relapse,
                             y = Relapse_prob_pred7)) +

               binaxis = "y",

        plot.subtitle = element_text(color = "grey30", size = 10),

             linetype = "dashed",
             color = "grey70") + 
  annotate(geom = "text", 
           x = 0.45,

Testing 5 predictors

From the 7 predictive features used in the previous calculation, 2 are usually difficult to obtain: LeftAtrial_Vol and EpiFat. These 2 features are calculated by diagnostic imaging, which is not always performed for all patients. In some cases, the physician does not have access to those measurements, which impairs the calculation of medical scores that require any of those values (eg. the ATLAS score).

This next test aims to evaluate the modelâs performance without those 2 features, hence simulating a frequent realâlife scenario.

Calculate relapse probabilities

For this step, we calculated the conditional probability of AF relapse for each patient at the test set, considering only 5 of its parent nodes: Age, Sex, Smoking_active, Persistent_AF, and OSA. The remaining 2 parent nodes LeftAtrium_Vol and EpiFat were disregard from evidence for the calculation of the conditional probabilities.

# Get parent nodes for "AF_relapse" from model
parent_nodes <-
  bnlearn::arcs(dag) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  dplyr::filter(to == "AF_relapse") %>%
  dplyr::select(from) %>%
  unlist() %>%
  unname()

# Create new column for computed relapse probabilities
ds_test[, "Relapse_prob_pred5"] <- NA

# Fill in probabilities variable
n_tries <- 10
n_means <- 5

for (patient in rownames(ds_test)) {
  evidence_patient <- ds_test[patient, parent_nodes]
  
  # Calculate probability of relapse as average of N queries to model
  Relapse_prob_pred5 <- array(NA, n_means)
  for (n in 1:length(Relapse_prob_pred5)) {
    Relapse_prob_pred5[n] <-
      sapply(matrix(NA, n_tries), FUN = function(x) {
        bnlearn::cpquery(fitted = fit.bayes,
                         event = (AF_relapse == TRUE),
                         evidence = ((Sex == evidence_patient$Sex) &
                                       (Age == evidence_patient$Age) &
                                       (Smoking_active == evidence_patient$Smoking_active) &
                                       (Persistent_AF == evidence_patient$Persistent_AF) &
                                       ### (LeftAtrium_Vol == evidence_patient$LeftAtrium_Vol) &
                                       ### (EpiFat == evidence_patient$EpiFat) &
                                       (OSA == evidence_patient$OSA))
                         )
      }) |> mean(na.rm = TRUE)
  }
  
  Relapse_prob_pred5 <- Relapse_prob_pred5 |> mean(na.rm = TRUE) |> round(digits = 3)
  ds_test[patient, "Relapse_prob_pred5"] <- Relapse_prob_pred5
}

Evaluate performance

model_roc_pred5 <- pROC::roc(ds_test$AF_relapse, ds_test$Relapse_prob_pred5)

Discussion

The model based on a Bayesian Network, built from both expert knowledge and data inference, shows a good discriminatory power for predicting the relapse of Atrial Fibrillation (AF) in patients after surgical ablation.

When using evidence from all the parent nodes of our outcome variable as predictors, the performs with a computed AUC value of 0.830.

Even in the absence of information on LeftAtrial_Vol and EpiFat as predictive features, the model shows a reasonable performance with a computed AUC value of 0.766. This simulation is particularly relevant, as those 2 predictive features are not always accessible to physicians for the calculation of relapse risk by using medical scores.

This model can be regarded as an enhancement of the ATLAS score, as it is based on its 5 predicting features, to which 2 other additional features were added. The Bayesian Network model has as advantages i) the possibility of being calculated even in cases of incomplete information (eg. when there is no information about the Left atrial volume), and 2) the possibility of being continuously retrained as new patient information is added to the model, hence expectably providing more accurate results as new evidence is included in the calculation.
